    # [Scene: Ruined Boardwalk | Glassy Dawn → Squall]

    scene bg ch15_3be532_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: High-tension percussion, rising wind strings]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A single gull cry cut off by a growing roar of surf; distant shouts under wind]
    "The dawn is a sheet of glass, and then it isn't. The horizon folds inward with a sudden, unnatural speed—light gone hard, sky pressed low. You taste electricity on your tongue before the rain starts: metal,"
    "ozone, the sharp bite of something imminent. It comes like a thrown thing and splinters into sound."
    "Elias 'Eli' Rowan's hands are a study in tremor and resolve. He straps the salvaged drone remote to his belt with fingers that refuse to stop moving. His goggles sit at a crooked angle above his"
    "brow; a smear of rain mud dries in the crease of his cheek. He doesn't look at you for a beat—then he does, and you see everything there: frantic hope, guilty fear, a promise he can't"
    "keep without you."

    "Elias 'Eli' Rowan" "We should launch it—get eyes on the north cul-de-sac. If the modular breakwaters failed, we'll need to know where the surge's weakest points are."
    "You want to argue the math, the trade-offs, the fact that the pilot systems were never intended to face a storm with this confluence of pressures. Instead, you nod and move. There's no room for theory now—only hands."
    show mara_kestrel at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_kestrel "Do it. But keep it high. Don't get it close to the spray. Rafi—get the line across the Thompson porch. That's three houses we can shore if the tide holds."

    "Elias 'Eli' Rowan" "Right. I'll—' (He palms the remote, breath fogging.) 'I'll keep it back. Mara, if it goes down, I'm going after it."

    mara_kestrel "Don't."
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A deep, metallic groan—somewhere a bulkhead gives—followed by a rush that feels like a wall barking at the town.]
    "You run. The boardwalk is wet and knives of splinter; your boots slip once, twice. Wind takes your hair and lashes it to your face. You taste the salt sharp as a warning. Neighbors move in"
    "quick, small lines—lanterns in plastic buckets, lengths of nylon, steel-reinforced plywood dragged like coffins. No one is spared the work. No one has time for pretense."
    "Rafi appears as if he'd been carved from the storm itself: hat flattened, beard a map of salt, hands already knotting. His voice is a wet bark."
    show rafi_gmez at right:
        zoom 0.7

    rafi_gmez "We lost the contractor crews. They pulled out when the water hit the foundation at basin four."

    mara_kestrel "Which pilot sites are still online?"

    rafi_gmez "Rain systems clogged at the Colemans. Breakwaters half-set at Harbor Lane—those pylons weren't driven deep enough. We had volunteers, but not the machines to finish."

    mara_kestrel "Then we triage.' (You feel the word like an old wound reopening.) 'Eli, Thompson porch. Rafi, Colemans—get their pumps moving even if it means we siphon from the desal trailers. I—"

    menu:
        "Send Eli to secure Thompson's porch with you":
            "Eli straightens, jaw set; his fingers close around yours for a fraction longer than necessary before he sprints toward the Thompson house."
        "Keep Eli on drone and send Rafi with you":
            "Eli's face tightens—relief and frustration cross him—and he jerks the drone into the sky while Rafi falls into step at your shoulder."

    # --- merge ---
    "Your throat is raw when you shout orders."
    "Your throat is raw when you shout orders. They spill out quick—plywood angles, sandbag lines, where to brace, where to channel the water. Your voice is a tool and a tether; it steadies those around you"
    "even as your chest gnaws with the ledger of what you cannot do. The modular breakwaters—so proud in your plans—are bunched like broken teeth, half-anchored, half-floating. Hoses kink, pumps falter beneath the sediment the storm has"
    "churned up. The pilot rain-catch systems clog with a hairline of debris and dead leaves faster than hands can clear them."

    "Neighbor A" "We got elderly on the second floor—can't carry 'em down in this!"

    "Neighbor B" "There! The seawall—it's split."

    "Neighbor C" "This is on the council! This is on the council for selling us a half-finished promise!"
    "Every sentence is both map and accusation. You feel the weight of each syllable. You feel Livia Chen's absence like a bruise at the center of town—no presence at the pumps, only the cold, bureaucratic rustle"
    "of legal counsel moving in other rooms. She is elsewhere: not because she doesn't care, but because power looks like paper now, and paper can be folded away from ruin."
    "Elias 'Eli' Rowan comes to your side, breath blowing rain; his hands are shaking so hard he can't wrap a bit of cord neatly."

    "Elias 'Eli' Rowan" "They were supposed to finish—Livia signed the contracts. The crews pulled, Mara. They—"

    mara_kestrel "We're not signing anything now.' (For a moment you're the scientist, the planner: a list of failed points, a record of what was promised and what was delivered.) 'We have to choose houses to shore. Two teams. One to the east cul-de-sac, one to the west. We patch, we pump, we pray."

    "Elias 'Eli' Rowan" "And if the seawall tears further?"

    mara_kestrel "Then we buy people time."

    menu:
        "Divert saved pumps to the elderly block":
            "Hands shift, someone curses, and the line moves—pumps go on a stretcher-run to the elder block; an old woman cries and thanks you like a benediction."
        "Prioritize homes with families and children":
            "Parents bundle kids into flannel and plex; a child presses a small, soaked toy into your palm with trust you cannot repay; Eli's jaw clenches and he moves like a man folding himself into purpose."

    # --- merge ---
    "The roar becomes a wall."
    "The roar becomes a wall. A break speaks in a language everything understands: a sound like glass and then a body of water that is not water but an animal breaking loose. The seawall gives near"
    "the old fisherman’s cut—an engineered hinge, or perhaps just a seam the tide found. The surge is a hand that brushes the boardwalk and keeps going, carrying with it the scent of petrol and the sudden"
    "iron of upturned soil. Sand, decking, a small wooden table with a child's cup clinging to its leg—gone."
    "For a beat the world is a strobe of falling things. People scream—some names, some raw sounds—and you move through them like a surgeon looking for a pulse. You shout, you drag, you find a rope"
    "and tie it to a lamppost that will not save anyone but will make a route for someone else to cling to."
    "Rafi is a machine of motion; his hands are everywhere: cutting, prying, wrapping. Between breaths he pulls you aside, voice a rough whisper."

    rafi_gmez "There's a wash that just took the Colemans' place. They were on the low side—two kids in there—"

    mara_kestrel "Where?"

    rafi_gmez "Past the laundromat. The pump's under twenty feet of—"
    "You feel the world condense into a set of failing levers: time, manpower, materials. The pilot breakwaters were a promise built in segments. They cannot, in their half-built geometry, stop a storm that chooses to wedge"
    "through their seams. The seawall, the contractor pauses, the delayed covenants—each is a small, dry twig that the wind uses to start its fire."
    "You shout and point and then you run towards a house where a light still blinks in the upstairs window. The water is ankle-deep and rises in the span of a stanza. You kick at a"
    "door and it gives. You climb, drag, throw a line over a beam. A woman clutches a child and a plastic tote of photos; she hands you the tote like a priest handing away relics."

    "Woman" "Take them. Please—"

    mara_kestrel "I will."
    "The break in the seawall sends a current that finds everything loose. A rowboat snaps free and hits the harbor piling like a broken jaw. A porch collapses. A dog disappears under a sheet of brown"
    "water. There are names later—losses catalogued in lists—but in this moment they are immediate: fingers peeking from under a washed-out doorway, the hollowed look of someone who has watched their life float by in a trash-rag"
    "tide."
    "Elias 'Eli' Rowan is beside you when the worst of it hits. He drags someone, knee deep, toward higher rafters; he moves with a speed that makes you think of the old city boys who ran"
    "when things fell apart. He helps a man up, then pauses and looks at you with a look that is not accusation but confession."

    "Elias 'Eli' Rowan" "I thought if I built smart things—if I could make a machine to do the work—we wouldn't have to beg for time."

    mara_kestrel "We still have to build.' (You are tired of saying it; it is a mantra that tastes like ash.) 'We needed more time, more people, fewer promises made without teeth."

    "Elias 'Eli' Rowan" "Promise me—' (He swallows.) 'Promise me you'll stay. Stay here—stay with me—"

    mara_kestrel "I—' (Words fail; the gravity of the storm makes all sentences small and inadequate.) 'I don't know if I can promise surviving the choices we made."
    "Elias 'Eli' Rowan reaches for you, hands wet and trembling; you let him. For a second the world narrows to the press of his palm and the hardness of your ribs under soaked fabric. Love is"
    "a small heat in the vast cold of what has been lost. It does not fix the seawall. It does not law the council. It is a witness, and witness will have to do."
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Percussion crescendos into a harsh, metallic arrest; then—silence in the middle of the roar for a breath]
    "The immediate storm passes like a recalled animal; the squall folds into a long, keening aftersound. Dawn, disfigured, finds itself again under a sky milky with exhausted light. The town is a new language of ruins:"
    "planks and twisted signage, a bakery façade collapsed into a tangle of flour and rain, a cross-hatched of sandbags like bruises."
    "You walk through a neighborhood that used to be ordinary and is now a ledger of absence. Doors hang open like empty mouths. A piano ruined by salt rain holds half a child's song. For hours—days—the"
    "town will be a list: names of people who left, who didn't, who were found. There will be doorways with personal things draped and missing, an inventory taken by hands that tremble."
    "Livia Chen's presence recedes into the paperwork that moves through lit rooms and away from the street. You hear the rumor first—then confirmation: the council is splintered; legal teams argue about liabilities and scope; Livia convenes"
    "stakeholders behind closed doors. Her absence at the pumps becomes, in the town's mind, a ledger of priorities she chose."

    mara_kestrel "She still has the council records. She still has the developers' phone numbers."

    "Elias 'Eli' Rowan" "That doesn't fix the boardwalk. It doesn't get people home."
    "Rafi appears with a list—names scrawled in salt-smudged ink. He looks at you with a tired smile that is almost feral."

    rafi_gmez "Some left with suitcases at three this morning. Some with nothing. We got people staying—Grandma Hira's got folks under her roof—but it's light. Houses will empty."

    mara_kestrel "How many—"

    rafi_gmez "Too many."
    "Night comes and does not soften anything. You and Eli climb to the Tidewatch lighthouse rooftop because the roof is a place that still holds air and because you need a place to breathe that isn't"
    "full of people asking for answers you don't have. The light at the top is a small banal relief: a lamp, a glinting thing that says the world is still orbiting."
    # [Scene: Tidewatch Lighthouse Rooftop | Night — Aftermath]
    hide mara_kestrel
    hide rafi_gmez

    scene bg ch15_3be532_2 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Slow, aching cello; a single high piano note repeating like a dropped bead]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The distant muffled conversations of neighbors, the low, steady slap of water on pilings]
    "You both sit with your backs to the low wall, clothes heavy with water, the salt of the day crusting your sleeves. Your hands find each other like a reflex. There is no triumph here—only the residue of choices, the cost accounted for in missing names."

    "Elias 'Eli' Rowan" "We tried to split the difference—pilot projects, covenants half-done, a seawall signed and paused. We thought being in the middle would save us."
    show mara_kestrel at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_kestrel "Being the hinge is a lonely, dangerous place. It makes you carry everyone's decisions as if you're their ledger. It makes you responsible for things you never had full control over."

    "Elias 'Eli' Rowan" "Do you regret—"

    mara_kestrel "I regret not having more time, more hands, more truthful promises."

    "Elias 'Eli' Rowan" "Us?"

    mara_kestrel "I am here. I'm with you now.' (You speak and mean it with a clarity that is both mercy and indictment.) 'But staying means living with the cost of decisions that weren't perfect. Love doesn't cancel debt. It doesn't cancel loss. It watches with you."
    "He rests his head on your shoulder, the rainwater in his hair cold against your neck. Love is a witness. It is also a bruise—warm, continuous, reminding you that two people can hold the same wrong and still choose to be together under it."
    "Below, the town makes its first fragile moves toward repair. There will be meetings—harsh ones—about responsibility. There will be families who never return. There will be an empty storefront you used to pass with Eli where"
    "he bought you a warm, ridiculous hat. There will be days when the cost of the choices you made is a hammer you cannot put down."
    "You close your eyes for a moment and see the faces: Rafi moving like a lighthouse himself, Grandma Hira humming in the doorway, the neighbor who handed you a plastic tote of photos. You see the faces of the ones who left and those who stayed. The ledger is long."

    "Elias 'Eli' Rowan" "We keep going. We keep building better, Mara. Or we leave. But whatever we do, we do it honest."

    mara_kestrel "Honesty is a start. It won't mend everything. It will make us bear it together."
    "You let the lighthouse's lamp sweep the ruined harbor. Its beam finds a child in a high window, an old man on a porch, a dog that has decided today is the day it will howl. The beam does not fix anything. It simply shows what is there."
